(2218, 'What-Happened-To-The-JonBenet-Ramsey-House', 'What Happened To The JonBenét Ramsey House?', '247 News Around The World 247 News Around The World In 2023, Dirt reported that John and Patsy Ramsey bought the spacious… The post What Happened To The JonBenét Ramsey House? appeared first on 247 News Around The World.', 'In 2023, Dirt reported that John and Patsy Ramsey bought the spacious home on a quarter-acre lot in Boulder, Colorado in 1991 for $500,000 and sold it about seven years later for $650,000, shortly after their daughter died. At that time, the home was bought by investors who changed the infamous property’s address and — given the high-profile nature of JonBenét Ramsey’s murder — made a number of other landscape changes over potential privacy issues. Meanwhile, the Milners bought the home for around $1 million in 2004 and listed it for sale in 2008, 2009, and 2011, for a bit more than $2 million, and again in 2014 for a bit less than $2 million. According to Velvet Ropes , the exterior of the home looks much the same as it did when the property was thrust into the spotlight during the height of the Ramsey murder spectacle, but the interior of the home has been completely redone. It’s now surrounded by tall trees and protected by an iron gate. Supporting the almost $7 million asking price, the multi-level home — made from red brick and white stucco — sits in one of the nicest areas of Boulder, near the University of Colorado Boulder and Boulder’s Chautauqua Park. It’s decked out with a media room, wet bar, wine cellar, and gourmet kitchen. University of Colorado’s speed, strength, and conditioning coach E.J. “Doc” Kreis rented the home for a time from 1999 through 2001, according to The Denver Post .', NULL, NULL, 'https://247newsaroundtheworld.com/crime/what-happened-to-the-jonbenet-ramsey-house/', '2023-07-09 08:11:02', 'united kingdom', NULL, '2023-07-09 17:09:57', '2023-07-09 17:09:57', 2, 'Crime', 'kitchener', 0),
(2219, 'Britain\'s-100-Best-Local-Restaurants-2023:-Kent-restaurant-Tallow-named-the-best-in-UK-full-list-of-winners', 'Britain’s 100 Best Local Restaurants 2023: Kent restaurant, Tallow named the best in UK - full list of winners', 'A restaurant in Kent has been named the best local restaurant by The Good Food Guide.', 'The Good Food Guide has named a restaurant in Kent as the best local restaurant in the UK. The prestigious list was compiled using 37,000 public nominations for restaurants in England, Scotland, and Wales, with each of the final 100 restaurants visited by guide inspectors. The Good Food Guide’s list of Britain’s 100 Best Local Restaurants includes many regional champions, including the overall winner, Tallow in Royal Tunbridge Wells, Southborough, Kent. Advertisement Hide Ad Advertisement Hide Ad Editor, Elizabeth Carter, said of the win: “Tallow stood out, head and shoulders above what is a very strong list this year. For a chef of this quality to be so happily focused on running a neighbourhood restaurant is extraordinary. “There’s a level of commitment here that would sit happily in many top restaurants. Everything is beautifully thought through, from food you really want to eat - delicious, simple, seasonal - the remarkable at ease service and the care of customers. Most Popular “The menu offers choice (a la carte or tasting), is affordable, completely changes each month, including the bread and the snacks; regulars like to visit at least once a month in order to try it out. Most live close enough to walk or are a short taxi ride away. They are very lucky.” Tallow owner, Donna Taylor, said: “What an unexpected and humbling acknowledgement for the whole team at Tallow, and such a privilege to be considered alongside restaurants we love and respect. Advertisement Hide Ad Advertisement Hide Ad “We’re incredibly proud to receive confirmation from our guests that Tallow has become what we had hoped, an accessible, relaxed dining experience that they wish to enjoy over and over again.” The Good Food Guide’s regional winners Central and East of England Tropea , Birmingham, West Midlands The Guide says: “A true neighbourhood restaurant in a well-heeled Birmingham suburb, with a genuinely welcoming vibe and excellent Italian cooking from a talented, locally trained chef.” A restaurant in Kent has been named the best local restaurant by The Good Food Guide. London Les 2 Garçons , Crouch End The Guide says: “London’s Best Local Restaurant is a gem of a French bistro that has soared to the top of the popularity stakes with its authentic cooking and endearing Gallic hospitality.” North East Homestead Kitchen , Goathland, North Yorkshire The Guide says: “With its fabulous views and its commitment to seasonal food, sustainability and all things local, this Yorkshire farmhouse restaurant is an outright regional winner.” North West The Spärrows , Green Quarter, Manchester Advertisement Hide Ad Advertisement Hide Ad The Guide says: “The decor may be Nordic and the food shot through with Central European generosity, but this is a properly local restaurant – and a real credit to Manchester.” Scotland The Kinneuchar Inn in Kilconquhar , Fife The Guide says: “Still part of the local scene, and a rare example of a genuine dining pub in Scotland, this amiable spot serves up eclectic dishes based on East Neuk’s seasonal larder.” South East Maidenhead, Berkshire The Guide says: “A beacon of local loveliness in Maidenhead town centre, this personally run restaurant is a godsend with its community feel, enthusiastic service and great-value cooking.” South West Wild Artichokes , Kingsbridge, Devon The Guide says: “Local means magical at this warmly hospitable south Devon restaurant, where shared tables, a fun-loving vibe and creative cooking make for a truly memorable experience.” Wales Rocket & Rye , Cowbridge, Glamorgan Advertisement Hide Ad Advertisement Hide Ad The Guide says: “Pitched somewhere between a café and a restaurant, John Cook’s upmarket eatery succeeds on all counts, making it a worthy local winner in Wales.” For the full top 100 restaurants list, visit the Good Food Guide website . Related topics: Kent Restaurants', 'https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/jpim-static/image/2023/07/09/13/gettyimages-1296818617-170667a.jpg?width=1200&auto=webp', NULL, 'https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/read-this/britains-100-best-local-restaurants-2023-kent-restaurant-tallow-named-the-best-in-uk-full-list-of-winners-4212443', '2023-07-09 06:56:13', 'united kingdom', NULL, '2023-07-09 17:09:57', '2023-07-09 17:09:57', 2, 'Read This', 'kitchener', 0),
(2220, 'Savor-your-coffee-someone-probably-lost-sleep-over-it', 'Savor your coffee; someone probably lost sleep over it', 'When I get up and make my first cup of coffee, I do it like performing a sacred ritual. I know that those beans traveled far, and were cared for.', 'Coffee fruit dries in the late-afternoon sun on a farm in the Brazilian state of Minas Gerais. Lucas Neves hide caption I have a kind of reverence for the coffee bean. Nearly every family trip we went on when I was a kid was spent flying across the planet from Boston to Rio de Janeiro, where almost my entire extended family lives. There aren\'t many coffee farms in the humid tropical climate of Rio, but if you drive out eight to 12 hours to the tiny town where my grandparents grew up in the state of Minas Gerais, you\'ll find arid rolling hills as far as you can see. That\'s where my cousins on my mom\'s side live, work and grow coffee. That trek — a five-hour flight, then an eight-hour flight, then a road trip — was always just the lead-up to the last leg of the journey. We\'d take the exhausted car and its passengers off the cobblestone streets, down a dirt road and to the top of a hill, where in my cousin\'s kitchen there would be at any hour of day or night some pão de queijo (or some cake) and a freshly poured thermos. Coffee fruit up close. Each one is a bit smaller than a cherry tomato. Lucas Neves hide caption We\'d drink the coffee out of little glass cups and finally get to work catching up and telling stories to one another. My parents would sit by the wood stove, and my brother and I would sometimes wander out while the adults were talking to chase the chickens and throw around a lemon like a tennis ball for the farm dogs to fetch. Coffee in Minas is usually served sickly sweet, but never with milk, and never iced, even in the middle of summer. Once the stars came out, we\'d soak them in until the air got cold, and then we\'d squeeze ourselves by the wood stove with another cup and feel a warm certainty that the coffee thermos must be bigger on the inside. Most of the highest-quality beans in Minas Gerais are sold abroad. When I was a kid especially, there wasn\'t really a coffee culture in Brazil the way there is in New York or Boston — that third-wave coffee culture that has a kind of purist bent to it, mindful of the \"notes\" in the brew. My coffee ritual these days: First, make sure you buy some actually nice coffee! I swear it\'s worth it. For brew method, lately I use a French press. Pour 60 mL (about 1/4 cup) water over the beans, stir and start timer. Let it bloom for 30 seconds; then pour the rest of the water to 250 mL (about 1 cup) and place the lid on the top. When the timer hits 4 minutes, gently press the plunger down and pour the coffee out into a cup. I like to drink it with 1/2 teaspoon of granulated sugar (I am not a purist! Only a ritualist). Enjoy on a comfortable perch, like a window with a view or a porch swing. But in college, I worked at a cafe that served the snooty tourists, students and professors in Harvard Square. And there I was taught to notice all those things I\'d never learned about coffee, even though I\'d seen the coffee fruit on the trees and watched firsthand as my cousins spread the fruit onto big, wavy multicolored sheets under the sun to dry. I learned then that my cousins\' process for preparing coffee was just one of many ways to do it — you could dry it in the sun or in a big machine, or it could be fermented, or washed first. All these methods could change the way the coffee tasted. I also learned that different regions have different taste profiles; some countries tend to be brighter, some earthier, some more complex or fruity. Brazil tends to be pretty soft, but more chocolatey and rich, like bourbon. I learned to think about tasting coffee as playing a word-association game. What does it make you think of? What memory comes up for you? Is there citrus? Or wood smoke? A coffee farm. Lucas Neves hide caption Today when I get up and make my first cup of coffee, I do it like performing a sacred ritual. I know that those beans traveled far, and were cared for. They were grown, and watered, and dried, and then roasted. Someone probably lost sleep over them when frost was in the forecast. It only feels right to me to measure out the beans on a scale, and grind them fresh, and make sure to let the beans bloom a bit before pouring the rest of the water over them. And when I take my first sip, I make sure to let my brain go blank, listen to the coffee and see where it takes me. What are you really into? Fill out this form or leave us a voice note at 800-329-4273, and part of your submission may be featured online or on the radio.', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.npr.org/2023/07/09/1183765334/coffee-farming-savoring', '2023-07-09 06:30:54', 'united states of america', NULL, '2023-07-09 17:09:57', '2023-07-09 17:09:57', 9, NULL, 'kitchener', 0),
(2221, 'India-News-or-2-Electrocuted-in-Sperate-Incidents-in-East-Delhi', 'India News | 2 Electrocuted in Sperate Incidents in East Delhi', 'Get latest articles and stories on India at LatestLY. A 60-year-old worker was electrocuted while working in the kitchen of a cafe in east Delhi\'s Preet Vihar area, police said on Sunday.', 'New Delhi, Jul 9 (PTI) A 60-year-old worker was electrocuted while working in the kitchen of a cafe in east Delhi\'s Preet Vihar area, police said on Sunday. Satender Negi, a resident of Mandawali, got electrocuted apparently by a geyser power board in the kitchen while keeping utensils in the rack at the cafe, they said. Also Read | Himachal Pradesh Flash Flood Videos: Five Killed in Landslides, All Major Rivers in Spate After Heavy Rainfall. Negi, who worked as a peon at the cafe in Block A of Preet Vihar, was rushed to Metro Hospital where he was declared brought dead, they said. Deputy Commissioner of Police (East) Amrutha Guguloth said the spot was inspected by the crime team and a case under section 304 A (causing death due to negligence) has been registered against unknown persons at Preet Vihar police station and an investigation is being carried out. Also Read | Uddhav Thackeray on NCP Split Says Waiting To See How BJP Handles Its New \'Riff-Raffs\'. In another incident, 28-year-old Mahipat, a resident of Firozabad in Uttar Pradesh got electrocuted at a sweet shop in east Delhi\'s Shakarpur area on Saturday, police said. The victim was working at the shop for the last 15 years. At the time of the incident, he was working on the second floor where he was using an electric grinder to grind spices and got an electric shock, the senior police officer said. The spot was inspected by the crime team, forensic and BSES team, she said. \"A case under section 304A (causing death due to negligence) and 34 (common intention) of the Indian Penal Code has been registered at Shakarpur police station against the sweet shop owner -- Rakesh Gupta and his son Naveesh Gupta. The investigation into the matter is underway,\" the DCP said. The information about his death was received from LNGP hospital, police said. Last month, Sakshi Ahuja (34) died after accidentally coming in contact with a live wire at the New Delhi Railway Station complex amid rainfall. This was the first incident of electrocution reported in the national capital this monsoon season. Following this, two more such incidents were reported. Delhi recorded 153 mm of rain in 24 hours ending 8:30 on Sunday, the highest in a single day in July since 1982, the India Meteorological Department said. An interaction between a western disturbance and monsoonal winds is leading to an intense rainfall spell over northwest India, including Delhi which experienced the season\'s first \"very heavy\" rainfall. (This is an unedited and auto-generated story from Syndicated News feed, LatestLY Staff may not have modified or edited the content body)', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.latestly.com/agency-news/india-news-2-electrocuted-in-sperate-incidents-in-east-delhi-5253617.html', '2023-07-09 06:30:30', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-09 17:09:57', '2023-07-09 17:09:57', 2, NULL, 'kitchener', 0),
(2235, 'Tiger-population-in-Sariska-touches-30-highest-till-date', 'Tiger population in Sariska touches 30, highest till date', 'Jaipur: The tiger population in Sariska hit its highest mark in three decades at 30 after two cubs were born to tiger ST-19. The trio was captured on camera in the buffer zone of the park near Alwar on July 6. The forest officials said that the father of these cubs is male tiger ST-18. […] The post Tiger population in Sariska touches 30, highest till date first appeared on Sambad English.', ': The tiger population in Sariska hit its highest mark in three decades at 30 after two cubs were born to tiger ST-19. The trio was captured on camera in the buffer zone of the park near Alwar on July 6. The forest officials said that the father of these cubs is male tiger ST-18. Chief Minister Ashok Gehlot took to Twitter and expressed his happiness. He also tagged the picture of the mother and the cubs. “New life in the forest. The good news of the birth of two cubs was received from Sariska. Now the number of tigers has increased to 30. The government is committed to the conservation of tigers which is important for the environment,” he tweeted in Hindi on Sunday. (IANS)', NULL, NULL, 'https://sambadenglish.com/tiger-population-in-sariska-touches-30-highest-till-date/', '2023-07-09 22:43:44', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, 'INDIA;TOP', 'jaipur', 0),
(2236, 'India-News-or-500-Teachers-of-Rajasthan-Govt-Colleges-to-Get-Trained-in-Reputed-Foreign-National-Institutions', 'India News | 500 Teachers of Rajasthan Govt Colleges to Get Trained in Reputed Foreign, National Institutions', 'Get latest articles and stories on India at LatestLY. Five hundred teachers of government-run colleges and polytechnic colleges in Rajasthan will now be able to take training courses in prestigious institutions of the country and abroad, said an official statement issued here on Sunday.', 'Jaipur, Jul 9 (PTI) Five hundred teachers of government-run colleges and polytechnic colleges in Rajasthan will now be able to take training courses in prestigious institutions of the country and abroad, said an official statement issued here on Sunday. The selected teachers will get to learn about the new technologies and innovations that could be applied while teaching students, the statement said. Also Read | Flash Floods in Himachal Pradesh: Rains Wreak Havoc in State, Six Dead in Landslides, Many Stranded. Chief Minister Ashok Gehlot has approved the proposal for the \'Teacher Interface for Excellence\' (TIE) programme in this regard, it added. Under the programme, Rs 23.50 crore will be spent on research and training facilities in the financial year 2023-24. The guidelines of the program will be issued soon, the release said. Also Read | School Holiday Due to Rain: All Schools in Delhi, Noida, Gurugram Closed Tomorrow Due to Rains. The TIE programme allows teachers to get training in prestigious foreign institutions with a QS (Quacquarelli Symonds) ranking of 1 to 100 and national institutions with a NIRF (National Institute Ranking Framework) ranking of 1 to 100, it added. “Teachers will be able to get acquainted and trained with excellent educational policies and programmes. This will encourage quality teaching and research in higher education in the state,\" the statement said. This programme will help improve the quality of education and research in the higher educational institutions of Rajasthan and further strengthen their performance in the grading provided by the National Assessment and Accreditation Council (NAAC), it added. The training programmes under TIE will be held for a period of 1 to 6 months, the government said. (This is an unedited and auto-generated story from Syndicated News feed, LatestLY Staff may not have modified or edited the content body)', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.latestly.com/agency-news/india-news-500-teachers-of-rajasthan-govt-colleges-to-get-trained-in-reputed-foreign-national-institutions-5254062.html', '2023-07-09 11:34:14', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2237, 'India-News-or-Man-Injured-as-Ruckus-Created-at-Religious-Event-over-Alleged-Conversion', 'India News | Man Injured as Ruckus Created at Religious Event over Alleged Conversion', 'Get latest articles and stories on India at LatestLY. A man was injured after a group of people allegedly created a ruckus at a religious event in Hanumangarh district, alleging Hindus and Sikhs were being converted to Christianity there, police said on Sunday.', 'Jaipur, Jul 9 (PTI) A man was injured after a group of people allegedly created a ruckus at a religious event in Hanumangarh district, alleging Hindus and Sikhs were being converted to Christianity there, police said on Sunday. They said the incident happened when several local Hindus, accusing the organisers converting people, entered the venue, a marriage garden in Pilibanga. Also Read | Flash Floods in Himachal Pradesh: Rains Wreak Havoc in State, Six Dead in Landslides, Many Stranded. They flung chairs and created a ruckus in which one person -- Samuel Masih -- was injured, police said, adding he has been admitted to a local government hospital. The two sides have filed counter FIRs. Also Read | School Holiday Due to Rain: All Schools in Delhi, Noida, Gurugram Closed Tomorrow Due to Rains. Pramod Mawar has alleged in his complaint that Hindus and Sikhs were being converted there, police said. The second FIR has been filed by Harbansh Lal who alleged that 250-300 people attacked the programme and hit the attendees who were listening to a religious broadcast from Jalandhar. Lal claimed in the FIR that around 15-20 people have been injured, but police said only one person was admitted to the hospital. Additional police force has been deployed in the area to maintain law and order, and the matter is being investigated. (This is an unedited and auto-generated story from Syndicated News feed, LatestLY Staff may not have modified or edited the content body)', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.latestly.com/agency-news/india-news-man-injured-as-ruckus-created-at-religious-event-over-alleged-conversion-5254013.html', '2023-07-09 11:04:15', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2238, 'School-Holiday-in-Gurugram:-All-Government-and-Private-Schools-in-District-to-Remain-Closed-Tomorrow-Due-to-Heavy-Rainfall', 'School Holiday in Gurugram: All Government and Private Schools in District to Remain Closed Tomorrow Due to Heavy Rainfall', 'Therefore, in consideration of the facts, all Government and Private Schools (including Play schools etc.) falling in the Gurugram district are hereby directed to remain closed tomorrow on 10th July in the larger public interest and for the safety & security of the students, the letter said.', 'Gurugram, July 9: Gurugram Deputy Commissioner (DC) Nishant Yadav on Sunday announced that all government, private and play schools will be shut for a day on Monday in Gurugram in view of incessant rain over the last two days. “On July 9 the District Gurugram experienced heavy & continuous rainfall and there is a prediction for heavy rainfall tomorrow (Monday) as well. The significant rainfall and the continuous forecast raise concerns regarding waterlogging, tree falling and disruption in civic amenities in several areas of the district,” the DC said. Gurugram School Holiday Due To Rains: All govt and Private Schools in District to Remain Closed on July 10 Following Heavy Rainfall. Therefore, in consideration of the facts, all Government and Private Schools (including Play schools etc.) falling in the Gurugram district are hereby directed to remain closed tomorrow on 10th July in the larger public interest and for the safety & security of the students, the letter said. Earlier on Sunday, the Gurugram administration issued an advisory to private institutions and corporate offices to guide their employees to Work From Home (WFH) on Monday to avoid traffic congestion on roads. Gurugram Rains: Admin Issues Work From Home Advisory to Corporate, Private Offices Due to Heavy Rainfall To Avoid Traffic Congestion (Watch Video). As per the data from the district administration Gurugram City recorded 150 mm of rain between 6.00 am and 11.00 am on Sunday which caused heavy water logging on the Delhi-Jaipur Expressway and different parts of the city. (The above story first appeared on LatestLY on Jul 09, 2023 09:46 PM IST. For more news and updates on politics, world, sports, entertainment and lifestyle, log on to our website latestly.com ).', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.latestly.com/india/news/school-holiday-in-gurugram-all-government-and-private-schools-in-district-to-remain-closed-tomorrow-due-to-heavy-rainfall-5253988.html', '2023-07-09 10:46:45', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2239, 'India-News-or-Student-Drown-in-Pit-Filled-with-Rainwater-in-Rajasthan\'s-Sikar', 'India News | Student Drown in Pit Filled with Rainwater in Rajasthan\'s Sikar', 'Get latest articles and stories on India at LatestLY. A 17-year-old student drowned after falling into a pit filled with rainwater in Rajasthan\'s Sikar city, police said on Sunday.', 'Jaipur, Jul 9 (PTI) A 17-year-old student drowned after falling into a pit filled with rainwater in Rajasthan\'s Sikar city, police said on Sunday. Yuvraj Singh was returning from his coaching on Saturday evening when he fell into the pit and drowned, Superintendent of Police Karan Sharma said. Also Read | Tigress Spotted With Two Cubs at Sariska Tiger Reserve, Rajasthan CM Ashok Gehlot Shares Pic. The pit was dug on Nawalgarh road for sewerage work, which got filled with rainwater. A team of civil defence brought the body out of the pit and shifted it to the mortuary of the district hospital. Meanwhile, locals assembled outside the hospital and demanded action against the guilty officials of Sikar municipal corporation and contractor. Also Read | Modi Government to Bring Back 150 Indian Artefacts from US in Next Six Months. A resident of Jhunjhunu, Yuvraj was preparing for the Joint Entrance Exam (JEE) in Sikar. His father is a CISF personnel. \"The family members have given a complaint against the municipal corporation officials and contractor and a case under section 304-A (causing death by negligence) has been registered,” SP Sharma said. However, the dharna is continuing with the protesters demanding compensation and government jobs to one family member, he said. (This is an unedited and auto-generated story from Syndicated News feed, LatestLY Staff may not have modified or edited the content body)', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.latestly.com/agency-news/india-news-student-drown-in-pit-filled-with-rainwater-in-rajasthans-sikar-5253892.html', '2023-07-09 09:38:16', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2240, 'Several-Dead-As-North-India-Rain-Washes-Away-Roads-And-Records', 'Several Dead As North India Rain Washes Away Roads And Records', 'Heavy rain will continue in most parts of northwest India over the next few days, the weather office has said.', 'North India Rains: Waterlogging led to traffic jams in several areas At least 12 people have died in the past two days as heavy rain pounded several parts of north India. The weather office has predicted more showers over the next couple of days. The Indian Metrological Department (IMD) has predicted heavy to extremely heavy rain for Delhi, Haryana, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Rajasthan, Punjab and Jammu and Kashmir. The IMD said a western disturbance prevailed over northern India, leading to an intense spell of rain yesterday, including Delhi which experienced the season\'s first heavy rain. Waterlogging led to traffic jams in several parts of the national capital. The city recorded 153 mm of rainfall in 24 hours, highest in single day in July since 1982. Heavy rain continued in Delhi and its adjoining areas today as well. Several parts of Gurugram also experienced waterlogging and power outages. Moderate rain is expected in Delhi tomorrow, said the weather department, adding that light rain is expected till July 15. A 58-year-old woman was killed in Delhi when the ceiling of her flat came crashing down on her, while four people died in rain-related incidents in Rajasthan. A woman and her six-year-old daughter were killed in Uttar Pradesh\'s Muzaffarnagar early this morning after their house collapsed due to heavy rain. Three of a family were killed in Himachal Pradesh\'s Shimla in a similar incident. In Jammu and Kashmir, two Army soldiers died after being swept away in flash floods in the Poonch district yesterday. The IMD has predicted very heavy rainfall in more than nine districts of Rajasthan, including, Rajsamand, Jalore, Pali, Ajmer, Alwar, Banswara, Bharatpur, Bhilwara, Bundi, Chittorgarh, Dausa, Dhaulpur, Jaipur and Kota. The annual Amarnath Yatra has been suspended for the third consecutive day today following incessant rains and landslides. About 3,000 vehicles are stranded along the Srinagar- Jammu Highway, where a portion of the road had caved in yesterday. Down south, Incessant rains pounded many areas of Kerala and Karnataka as well. The IMD has issued a \"yellow\" alert in four districts of Kerala -- Kozhikode, Wayanad, Kannur and Kasaragod. The weather office has issued a \"red\" alert for seven Himachal Pradesh districts after landslides and flash floods blocked several roads in Shimla, Sirmaur, Lahaul and Spiti, Chamba and Solan. Promoted Listen to the latest songs, only on JioSaavn.com A portion of the national highway in Kullu district washed away as the Beas river breached the danger mark. Heavy rain lashed several parts of Haryana and Punjab also as the mercury dropped below normal limits in the two states, the weather office said. Chandigarh, the common capital of the two states, witnessed rain throughout the day.', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/heavy-rain-batters-north-india-more-showers-predicted-today-4190636#publisher=newsstand', '2023-07-09 09:28:57', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2241, '9-Best-Places-To-Celebrate-A-Milestone-Birthday', '9 Best Places To Celebrate A Milestone Birthday', 'For those who love to accumulate experiences over material things, consider traveling to one of these fantastic destinations to celebrate a milestone birthday.', 'Forbes Lifestyle Travel 9 Best Places To Celebrate A Milestone Birthday Wendy Altschuler Contributor Opinions expressed by Forbes Contributors are their own. I cover travel, adventure, and culture across the globe, specializing in nature and the great outdoors. Following Jul 9, 2023, 10:58am EDT | Press play to listen to this article! Got it! Share to Facebook Share to Twitter Share to Linkedin India, Rajasthan getty While every birthday is cause for merriment, milestone birthdays necessitate a bit more pomp and circumstance. For many, it can feel like a big deal to enter into a new decade. Energetic and lively destinations like New Zealand and Spain are great for when you’re in your twenties. Cultural tours through India or Thailand are perfect for exploring in your thirties. Luxury ranches in Montana, private tours in the UAE, and brand-new properties in Singapore are just the thing for well-heeled folks in their fifties. Of course, Paris and Vienna are always a good idea. No matter what age bracket you’re reveling in, however, you’ll never regret marking the special occasion in a grand way. For those who love to accumulate experiences over material things, consider traveling to one of these fantastic destinations to celebrate a milestone birthday. Singapore Singapore, Merlion Statue getty An island country in southeast Asia, many travelers put Singapore at the top of their bucket list after seeing the movie Crazy Rich Asians. Well worth the visit, especially to celebrate your birthday, this city-state has much to see, from popular attractions like Gardens by the Bay, Cloud Forest, Singapore Flyer, and Universal Studios Singapore. The modern architecture is also quite stunning—the Helix Footbridge, Marina Bay Sands, and Esplanade for starters. Singapore, a beautiful walkable city with great public transportation, is modern, clean, and oh-so green. Pro Tip: To maximize your time and get the most for your buck, secure a Go City all-inclusive pass, which will grant you access to fun hot spots like the Flower Dome and Avatar Experience at Gardens by the Bay. Where to Stay: New to the scene, Pan Pacific Orchard, Singapore is a destination in itself where architectural delights abound through four well-designed nature-forward stacked environments: Forest, Beach, Garden, and Cloud. When you’re not lounging on your room’s luxe balcony, swimming in the outdoor pool, or enjoying a cocktail in the jewel-toned Florette, you’ll be dining in Mosella , open for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. This whimsical luxury hotel has to be seen to be believed. MORE FOR YOU New Apple Leak Confirms iPhone 15 Price Shock Today’s ‘Quordle’ Answers And Clues For Sunday, July 9 Crimean-Congo Hemorrhagic Fever, CCHF, Virus Spreading In Europe Due To Climate Change North Island, New Zealand An early morning view of Auckland. getty New Zealand’s North Island is an adventurer’s paradise, full of mountain biking, ziplining, and hiking. From exceptional dining opportunities in Auckland, the country’s largest city, to wine tasting on Waiheke Island, scrambling on Rangitoto Island, sailing at Taupo, and soaking in thermal pools in Rotorua , there’s much to experience on this wild and fern-filled island. Grab your outdoorsy besties and enter a new decade in a festive way. Pro Tip: A member of Star Alliance (United Airlines), Air New Zealand has non-stop flights from six major US cities. Montana The Resort at Paws Up, Montana Wendy Altschuler Perhaps the best way to celebrate your birthday with kids in tow is through a classic dude ranch experience with acres upon acres of tree-filled wilderness at your feet. From trail riding to cattle drives, cowboy cookouts to fine dining, white water rafting to fly fishing, Montana’s The Resort at Paws Up is just the nature-filled escape you’re yearning for. Blow out your birthday candles while staying in a luxury ranch home, where you’ll spend quality time with your family exploring the ranch’s adventuresome activities during the day and star gazing during a relaxing soak in the outdoor hot tub at night. Go ahead, you’ve earned it! Pro Tip: Time your visit with one of the resort’s many special events held throughout the year. From wilderness workshops to live music to culinary happenings, it’s all here. India The Taj Mahal getty Exploring India’s Golden Triangle, a well-traveled circuit that includes New Delhi, Agra, and Jaipur, is on many travelers’ wish-lists. Who wouldn’t want to see Old Delhi’s narrow streets via rickshaw; shop for incense, spices, and textiles on a walking tour through Chandni Chowk; and wander the grounds of Humayun’s Tomb and the Red Fort? What adventurer’s catalog doesn’t include Fatehpur Sikri or the perfectly symmetrical Taj Mahal in Agra? And no visit to India is complete without experiencing the wonder of “The Pink City”, Jaipur. Marvel at the Hawa Mahal, The City Palace, and Amber Palace. Pro Tip: To seamlessly weave all three cities together and experience the best of the Golden Triangle on a custom tour, employ the expert services of The Leela Palace New Delhi and The Leela Palace Jaipur . Both art-filled properties have stellar service, amenities, and exclusive dining opportunities. With The Leela Palace Trail, the professional team can curate a bespoke multi-day itinerary, including airport transfers, guides, and cultural experiences. Dubai Desert Safari Platinum Heritage Dubai Whether you’re visiting the UAE for several nights or you’re just popping in for a layover, be sure to make time for a desert safari. Platinum Heritage Dubai , a leading eco-luxury safari, makes visiting the region’s desert habitat stress-free. Your guide will pick you up from your hotel— The 25hours Hotel One Central is a solid choice, especially for celebrating a milestone birthday—and bring you to the conservation reserve where you’ll hop in a vintage Land Rover and explore the wilderness ecosystem in style. This inimitable once-in-a-lifetime experience also includes an educational falconry demonstration, exclusive Emirati cuisine at a Bedouin camp, a short camel ride, interactive musical performances, and more. Your friendly guide will be with you from start to finish, enlightening you about the distinctive flora and fauna along the way. Vienna, Austria Cityscape image of Vienna, Austria getty Vienna’s youthful energy has a way of grabbing hold of you while, at the same time, allowing you to appreciate the history and architecture that this capital city is known for. Situated along the Danube River, this artistic and intellectual hub is not only known for its famous past residents—Mozart, Beethoven, and Sigmund Freud, but also, its imperial palaces, museums, and cathedrals. Explore Belvedere Palace, see the Spanish Riding School, snap photos of the Vienna Operahouse, gaze at St Stephen’s Cathedral’s spires, and try the wiener schnitzel. You’ll love how walkable the city is as well as how easy it is to get around via public transportation. Where to Stay : Bold and beautiful, with multi-hued art-filled community spaces set in a modern building, SO/Vienna is chic with monochromatic luxe accommodations. Well located, with a beautiful rooftop restaurant and bar, Das LOFT, this brilliant hotel is ideal for any birthday celebration. Paris Paris getty Any time is a good time to visit Paris, but this sentiment is especially true for a birthday celebration. Do yourself a favor and book accommodations at Maison Colbert , Melia Collection. Located in the Latin Quarter, within easy walking distance to the Notre-Dame Cathedral and Shakespeare and Company independent bookstore and café, this 16 th -Century boutique hotel is on a quiet street, away from the chatter of the city. There’s a lovely courtyard, with outdoor seating, a café that serves delicious espresso and croissants in addition to a lovely breakfast buffet, and amenable staff that are ready help at a moment’s notice. Bangkok, Thailand Bangkok at night getty The first thing you’ll notice about Bangkok, one of the most-loved metropolises to visit in Southeast Asia, is how colorful and vibrant the chaotic atmosphere is, especially at night. See The Grand Palace, Chinatown, the country’s largest reclining buddha at Wat Pho, Wat Arun, and one of the hectic markets. After negotiating the fare beforehand, grab a tuk-tuk and explore the city in a gritty, wind-in-your-face kind of way. While touristy to be sure, stroll Khao San Road, the “backpacker capital of the world”, where noisy bars compete for your attention, hawkers too, and street food is easy to be found. Madrid, Spain Madrid, Spain getty Nightlife abounds in Spain’s capital city. Explore Madrid’s wide boulevards and trimmed parks by day and then sip cocktails and listen to live music by night. Nestled in the heart of the city, near the Royal Palace and the Opera House, Palacio de los Duques Gran Melia is a show stopper with its handsome garden and Restaurant Dos Cielos Madrid, located in what was once the old palace stables. This historic building was once the Santo Domingo convent and later the private residences of art collectors. You’ll love the opulent and mysterious-feeling interior, full of artworks and theatrical public spaces. Check out my website . Wendy Altschuler Editorial Standards Print Reprints & Permissions', 'https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/64aac6bf618c6fb96391cf1d/0x0.jpg?width=960', NULL, 'https://www.forbes.com/sites/wendyaltschuler/2023/07/09/9-best-places-to-celebrate-a-milestone-birthday/', '2023-07-09 09:28:10', 'united states of america', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 1, 'Travel;/travel;Lifestyle;/lifestyle;Travel;/travel;lifestyle;wendyaltschulerblog;standard', 'jaipur', 0),
(2242, 'How-Rooftop-created-a-new-canvas-for-learning-art', 'How Rooftop created a new canvas for learning art', 'Entrepreneur Kartik Gaggar has curated a rich tapestry of art experiences on his online platform', 'By Mohammed Rayaan Comments READ LATER Imagine a platform where you can match brushstrokes with the top exponents of Pichwai, Phad, Bhil and other folk art forms. Chartered accountant turned entrepreneur Kartik Gaggar’s online art learning start-up Rooftop allows you to do just that. Through its live workshops and curated courses, Rooftop has organised over 2,000 art experiences, featuring the expertise of more than 2,100 master artists. It has a membership of 42,800+ participants hailing from over 20 countries worldwide and opened up a new canvas of learning for art enthusiasts. How did a CA who articled with PwC get into the space of art? Gaggar says he harboured a profound passion for the arts from a young age. In the sea of online learning ventures, he spotted a gap in the realm of Indian arts and crafts education, and decided to bridge the gap between aspiring learners and the cultural custodians. At first, he initiated a Facebook page where like-minded individuals could partake in immersive ‘art experiences’ — city walks and art tours that unveiled the hidden artistry thriving within localities. At one point, he held such walks in Jaipur, Jodhpur and Udaipur. During the course of his research, Gaggar embarked on a transformative journey, engaging with artists and started documenting their creative processes. This odyssey eventually birthed the ‘Circle Community’ in 2020. However, destiny had its own plans as the world faced the pandemic. Gaggar swiftly adapted to the circumstances. “I consider those periods as moments of growth,” he reflects. Henceforth, his brainchild was christened ‘Rooftop’ — a place where families often congregate to learn, play, eat or chat. The platform’s original vision was to “establish an exclusive community that united local artisans, providing them with a platform to showcase their artistry.” Gaggar says that Rooftop app is owned by a bootstrapped company called Slo-Mo Experiences. The platform was launched with an investment of ₹2.5 crore and ever since its launch, it has witnessed a 5x year-on-year growth. “In January 2022, Rooftop launched the updated version of its app. In the first six months of FY23-24, the app aims to have a turnover of ₹4-5 crore and then scale it further,” says a company statement. Rooftop operates on a subscription and pay-as-you-go model for its art workshops. Gaggar elaborates on the revenue streams, stating, “Apart from collaborating with businesses for workshops, our primary source of income stems from course sales.” He highlights the prominence of ‘Maestro courses’ as one of their flagship offerings. “These maestro courses, meticulously curated by award-winning veteran artists, boast over 10 hours of recorded content. By embarking on these courses, participants not only master traditional art forms but also immerse themselves in the rich tapestry of tradition and culture underlying them,” Gaggar reveals. Moreover, Rooftop actively engages with corporate entities operating under a B2B model that centres around fostering employee engagement through art-related activities. Since its inception, Rooftop has garnered interest not only from art enthusiasts but also from prominent governmental bodies such as the Tourism Department and the Ministry of Culture. As part of the ‘Startup India Innovation Week 2022’, Gaggar presented policy recommendations in the Travel and Tourism sector on the theme ‘Local to Glocal’ in a virtual meeting with Prime Minister Narendra Modi. Rooftop has even signed MoUs with Manipal University, Jaipur and collaborated with top institutes like Sir JJ School of Arts, Nottingham Trent University, UK, and Jamia Millia Islamia University, Delhi. “We even conducted workshops for Google and have collaborations with Genpact and Bain Capital,” Gaggar adds. He envisions a platform that empowers art lovers to access immersive art workshops on-the-go while simultaneously enabling artisans to forge alternative sources of income. “Our future endeavours aim to establish art as an asset class model,” says Gaggar. Comments', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/catalyst/how-rooftop-created-a-new-canvas-for-learning-art/article67060717.ece', '2023-07-09 07:44:32', 'india', NULL, '2023-07-10 06:44:40', '2023-07-10 06:44:40', 2, NULL, 'jaipur', 0),
(2275, 'Dollar-witnesses-upsurge-in-interbank-market', 'Dollar witnesses upsurge in interbank market', 'The interbank market witnessed an increase of 60 paise, pushing the date rate to Rs278.50.', 'Karachi: The value of the US dollar continues to surge against the Pakistani rupee in the interbank market, marking a consecutive third-day increase. According to currency dealers, on the first day of the trading week, the dollar witnessed a rise of 60 paise in the interbank market, reaching PKR 278.50. It should be noted that last week also saw a record increase in the dollar exchange rate during the last two trading days. While previously, there had been a downward trend in the dollar\'s value due to the influence of international monetary funds. On the other hand, the Pakistan Stock Exchange experienced a bullish trend at the beginning of the trading session, with the KSE-100 index surging over 200 points to reach 44,440 points.', 'https://gnnhd.tv/media/67702/06114335fcb75f4.jpg', NULL, 'https://gnnhd.tv/news/22077/dollar-witnesses-upsurge-in-interbank-market', '2023-07-10 00:32:35', 'pakistan', NULL, '2023-07-10 07:00:04', '2023-07-10 07:00:04', 1, 'Business', '', 0),
(2276, 'NEPRA-okays-hike-in-power-tariff-by-Rs1.24-per-unit', 'NEPRA okays hike in power tariff by Rs1.24 per unit', 'The increased tariff will make the consumers suffer by Rs46.76 billion.', 'Islamabad: National Electric Power Regulatory Authority (NEPRA) again increased the prices of electricity by Rs1.24 per unit on Monday fulfilling the conditions of International Monetary Fund (IMF), GNN reported. According to details, the energy rate has been increased under the purview of quarter fuel adjustment charges which will be applicable on the bills of months July, August and September. The increased tariff will make the consumers suffer by Rs46.76 billion. After the implementation, the minimum rate of per unit will increase from Rs24 to Rs25, while the maximum rate will increase from Rs40 to settle at Rs42. Earlier on July 5, the power tariff was increased by Rs1.90 per unit. While on July 4, Rs1.25 was added in the price of electricity.', 'https://gnnhd.tv/media/67701/63785c4a7f6a2.jpg', NULL, 'https://gnnhd.tv/news/22076/nepra-okays-hike-in-power-tariff-by-rs124-per-unit', '2023-07-10 00:32:33', 'pakistan', NULL, '2023-07-10 07:00:04', '2023-07-10 07:00:04', 1, 'Business', '', 0),
(2277, 'News24.com-or-WATCH-or-Why-the-NHI-wants-your-medical-aid-premium', 'News24.com | WATCH | Why the NHI wants your medical aid premium', 'If the National Health Insurance (NHI) Bill is passed in its current form, your medical aid will disappear in its current form. It’s not clear how the NHI will be funded, but raised taxes will be unavoidable — and the scheme will likely want your medical aid premium.', 'If the National Health Insurance (NHI) Bill is passed in its current form, your medical aid will disappear in its current form. Medical schemes will only be allowed to fund \"top-up\" services, so health services that aren’t covered by the NHI. How will the state pay for the NHI? That’s not clear, but raised taxes will be unavoidable, and payroll taxes, for both employees and employers are on the cards. Essentially, the NHI wants your medical aid premium. This story was produced by the Bhekisisa Centre for Health Journalism. Sign up for the newsletter.', 'https://scripts.24.co.za/img/sites/news24.png', NULL, 'https://www.news24.com/news24/Video/SouthAfrica/News/watch-why-the-nhi-wants-your-medical-aid-premium-20230710', '2023-07-10 00:30:24', 'south africa', NULL, '2023-07-10 07:00:04', '2023-07-10 07:00:04', 2, NULL, '', 0);
